==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*walt-''.  Cognate with Old Saxon [[waldan]], Old High German [[waltan]] (German [[walten]]), Old Norse [[valda]] (Swedish [[vålla]]), Gothic [[𐍅𐌰𐌻𐌳𐌰𐌽]].

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/wæaldan/}}

===Verb===
'''wealdan''' (class VII strong: ''3 singular present'' '''[[wielt]]''', ''3 singular preterite'' '''[[weold|wēold]]''', ''preterite plural'' '''[[weoldon|wēoldon]]''', ''past participle'' '''[[wealden]]''')
# to [[rule]], [[manage]], [[control]], [[wield]]
#:''He weoldon wælstowe.''  They commanded the field.  (Beowulf)

===Descendants===
*English [[wield]]

